.TH "KEYS\-VAULT" "1" "" "keys\-vault 1.0.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
keys\-vault \[em] create and manage encrypted directories with
passphrase stored in GNOME Keyring
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]keys\-vault\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] \f[I]command\f[R]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]keys\-vault\f[R] is a command\-line tool that creates and manages
encrypted directories using \c
.UR https://github.com/rfjakob/gocryptfs
gocryptfs
.UE \c
\&.
Encrypted ciphertext is stored in a hidden \f[CR].enc\f[R] directory
alongside the plaintext mount point.
Passphrases are stored and retrieved automatically via GNOME Keyring
(using \f[CR]secret\-tool(1)\f[R]), so the vault can be mounted without
manual password entry.
.PP
The binary is implemented entirely in x86_64 assembly with direct Linux
syscalls \[em] no C library dependency.
See the project README for important notes about the experimental nature
of this implementation.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
\f[B]init\f[R]
Create a new encrypted volume and store the passphrase in GNOME Keyring.
The user is prompted to choose between a randomly generated passphrase
(recommended) or a user\-supplied one.
Refuses to initialize if the plaintext directory is not empty or if a
volume already exists at the target location.
.TP
\f[B]open\f[R]
Mount the vault using the passphrase retrieved from GNOME Keyring.
Automatically recovers stale FUSE mounts (where the gocryptfs process
has died but the mountpoint remains).
Prints a message and exits silently if already mounted or not
initialized.
.TP
\f[B]close\f[R]
Unmount the vault.
Handles stale mounts by force\-unmounting if necessary.
Exits silently if the vault is not mounted.
.TP
\f[B]status\f[R]
Print the current state to standard output.
Possible states: : \f[B]open\f[R] \[em] vault is mounted and accessible
: \f[B]locked\f[R] \[em] vault exists but is not mounted :
\f[B]stale\f[R] \[em] FUSE mount exists but the backing process has died
: \f[B]not initialized\f[R] \[em] no vault has been created at this
location
.TP
\f[B]passwd\f[R]
Rotate the gocryptfs passphrase and update the corresponding GNOME
Keyring entry.
Prompts for a new passphrase (with confirmation) and uses the existing
keyring entry to authenticate the rotation.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-\-dir\f[R]=\f[I]PATH\f[R]
Set the plaintext mount point.
Overrides the value from configuration files.
Default: \f[B]\[ti]/keys\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\-\-cipher\-dir\f[R]=\f[I]PATH\f[R]
Set the encrypted ciphertext directory.
Overrides the derived default.
By default, the cipher directory is derived from the plaintext path as a
hidden directory with a \f[B].enc\f[R] suffix in the same parent
directory (e.g., \f[CR]\[ti]/keys\f[R] → \f[CR]\[ti]/.keys.enc\f[R],
\f[CR]\[ti]/secure/vault\f[R] → \f[CR]\[ti]/secure/.vault.enc\f[R]).
.TP
\f[B]\-h\f[R], \f[B]\-\-help\f[R]
Show usage information and exit.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-version\f[R]
Show the version number and exit.
.SH CONFIGURATION
Configuration is read from the following files, in order.
Later values override earlier ones:
.IP "1." 3
\f[B]/etc/keys\-vault.conf\f[R] \[em] system\-wide defaults
.IP "2." 3
\f[B]$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/keys\-vault.conf\f[R] (default:
\f[B]\[ti]/.config/keys\-vault.conf\f[R]) \[em] per\-user overrides
.PP
Command\-line flags (\f[CR]\-\-dir\f[R], \f[CR]\-\-cipher\-dir\f[R])
take precedence over all configuration files.
.SS Format
Configuration files use a simple key\-value format:
.IP
.EX
PLAIN_DIR = /path/to/plain/dir
CIPHER_DIR = /path/to/cipher/dir
.EE
.IP \[bu] 2
Lines beginning with \f[CR]#\f[R] are comments.
.IP \[bu] 2
Blank lines are ignored.
.IP \[bu] 2
Whitespace around the \f[CR]=\f[R] sign is optional and is trimmed.
.IP \[bu] 2
Values may be quoted with single or double quotes (quotes are stripped).
.IP \[bu] 2
Inline comments (text after a space followed by \f[CR]#\f[R]) are
stripped.
.IP \[bu] 2
Unknown keys are silently ignored with a warning.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[CR]$HOME\f[R], \f[CR]${HOME}\f[R], and \f[CR]\[ti]\f[R] are expanded
in path values.
.SS Variables
.TP
\f[B]PLAIN_DIR\f[R]
Plaintext mount point where decrypted files are accessible.
Default: \f[B]$HOME/keys\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]CIPHER_DIR\f[R]
Directory where encrypted files are stored.
Default: derived from \f[CR]PLAIN_DIR\f[R] (hidden \f[CR].enc\f[R]
suffix in the same parent).
.SH STALE MOUNT RECOVERY
If the gocryptfs process dies unexpectedly (for example, due to an OOM
kill), the FUSE mountpoint becomes stale \[em] it remains visible in
\f[CR]/proc/mounts\f[R] but \f[CR]stat(2)\f[R] operations fail with
\[lq]Transport endpoint is not connected\[rq].
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]open\f[R] detects stale mounts and force\-unmounts them
(\f[CR]fusermount \-uz\f[R]) before attempting to re\-mount.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]close\f[R] also detects and handles stale mounts.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]status\f[R] reports \f[B]stale\f[R] as a distinct state so the user
is aware of the condition.
.SH GNOME KEYRING
Passphrases are stored in GNOME Keyring via \f[CR]secret\-tool(1)\f[R].
Each vault directory receives a unique keyring entry identified by its
resolved plaintext path.
The keyring attribute format is \f[CR]keys\-vault:<path>\f[R].
.PP
For automatic keyring unlock on login, ensure GNOME Keyring (or another
Secret Service provider such as \f[CR]gnome\-keyring\-daemon\f[R]) is
running and unlocked.
A typical setup uses PAM integration to unlock the keyring at session
start.
.SH EXAMPLES
Initialize and open a vault at the default location:
.IP
.EX
keys\-vault init
keys\-vault open
.EE
.PP
Use a custom directory:
.IP
.EX
keys\-vault \-\-dir=\[ti]/secure/credentials init
keys\-vault \-\-dir=\[ti]/secure/credentials open
.EE
.PP
Configure via configuration file:
.IP
.EX
echo \[aq]PLAIN_DIR = $HOME/secure/credentials\[aq] > \[ti]/.config/keys\-vault.conf
keys\-vault init
.EE
.PP
Check the current state:
.IP
.EX
keys\-vault status
.EE
.PP
Rotate the passphrase:
.IP
.EX
keys\-vault passwd
.EE
.PP
Unmount:
.IP
.EX
keys\-vault close
.EE
.SH FILES
.TP
\f[B]/etc/keys\-vault.conf\f[R]
System\-wide configuration file.
Installed by default during \f[CR]make install\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\[ti]/.config/keys\-vault.conf\f[R]
Per\-user configuration file.
Overrides system\-wide defaults.
